regi_algo.description:
TG: REGI

Authentication and Key Agreement procedure for IMS Registration.
If set to "none", registration algorithm is not pushed into SIP Authorization header of first REGISTER at all.
In that case UE relies on 401 response from network, which contains selected algorithm.
Second (encrypted) REGISTER contains algorithm within SIP Authorization header.

auth_algo.description:
TG: REGI

Authentication Algorithm for IPSec ESP
According to 3GPP TS 33.203 clause S.5.4.2.2 it con NOT be set to "none".
Can be set either to one of particular algorithm:
    - either hmac-md5-96,
    - or hmac-sha-1-96,
or set to container-like value "both" (which means both "hmac-md5-96" & "hmac-sha-1-96" are proposed by UE and any of them will be accepted by UE).
When value is set neither in default section nor in operator section, "both" value is taken as a fallback-default.

enc_algo.description:
TG: REGI

Encryption Algorithm for IPSec ESP
Can be set either to one of particular algorithm:
    - either "des-ede3-cbc",
    - or "aes-cbc",
    - or "none"          (which means IPSec encryption "null" is proposed/accepted by UE),
or to on of container-like values:
    - either "both"      (which means both "aes-cbc" & "des-ede3-cbc" are proposed by UE and any of them will be accepted by UE),
    - or "all"           (which means both "aes-cbc" & "null" are proposed by UE and any of them will be accepted by UE).
When value is set neither in default section nor in operator section, "all" value is taken as a fallback-default.

reregi_on_ratchange.description:
TG: REGI

Possible values are on (default, int 2 in code), off (int 0 in code) and off_rat_change (int 1 in code).

Difference between off and off_rat_change is that for the latter,
the RAT change is checked and only when it is present, the registration will be held
(during execution of UpdateRegistration method).

amrnboa_max_red.description:
TG: CALL

The 'max-red' SDP parameter for AMR octet-align codec.

The maximum duration in milliseconds that elapses between the primary (first) transmission of a frame and any redundant transmission that the sender will use.
This parameter allows a receiver to have a bounded delay when redundancy is used.
Allowed values are between 0 (no redundancy will be used) and 65535.

Reference: RFC 4867

evs_channel_aware_receive.description:
TG: CALL

If a positive (2, 3, 5, or 7) value of ch-aw-recv is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the receiver of the parameter shall send partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) at the start of the session using the value as the offset.
If ch-aw-recv=0 is declared or not present for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the receiver of the parameter shall not send partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) at the start of the session.
If ch-aw-recv=-1 is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the receiver of the parameter shall not send partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) in the session.
If not present or a non-negative (0, 2, 3, 5, or 7) value of ch-aw-recv is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, partial redundancy (channel-aware mode) can be activated or deactivated during the session based on the expected or estimated channel condition through adaptation signaling, such as CMR (see Annex A.2 of [125]) or RTCP based signalling (see clause 10.2).
If not present or a non-negative (0, 2, 3, 5, or 7) value of ch-aw-recv is declared for a payload type and the payload type is accepted, the partial redundancy offset value can also be adjusted during the session based on the expected or estimated channel condition through adaptation signaling.

TG: CALL

CMR (Codec Mode Request )
If cmr=-1 and the session is in the EVS Primary mode, MTSI client in terminal shall not transmit CMR. If cmr=-1 and the session is in the EVS AMR-WB IO, MTSI client in terminal shall restrict CMR to values of EVS AMR-WB-IO bit-rates and

evs_bit_rate_send.description:
TG: CALL

Specifies the range of source codec bit-rate [kb/s] for EVS Primary mode.
The parameter can either have: a single bit-rate (br1);
or a hyphen-separated pair of two bit-rates (br1-br2)
If a single value is included, this bit-rate, br1, is used.
If a hyphen-separated pair of two bit-rates is included,
br1 and br2 are used as the minimum bit-rate and the maximum bit-rate respectively.
br1 and br2 have a value from the set: 5.9, 7.2, 8, 9.6, 13.2, 16.4, 24.4, 32, 48, 64, 96, and 128.
(TS 26 445)

evs_bandwidth_send.description:
TG: CALL

Bandwidth in send direction
The session should start with the maximum bandwidth supported by the initial
bit-rate up to the maximum negotiated bandwidth.
If a range of bandwidth is negotiated, the codec can operate in any bandwidth
in the session but the maximum bandwidth in the range
should be used after the start of or update of the session.
If a single audio bandwidth higher than narrowband is negotiated,
the codec operates in the negotiated bandwidth but can use lower bandwidth(s)
in the session, depending on the input signal.

evs_default_bandwidth.description:
TG: CALL

Default EVS bandwidth
The session should start with the maximum bandwidth supported by the initial bit-rate up to the maximum negotiated bandwidth. If a range of bandwidth is negotiated, the codec can operate in any bandwidth in the session but the maximum bandwidth in the range should be
used after the start of or update of the session. If a single audio bandwidth higher than narrowband is negotiated, the codec operates in the negotiated bandwidth but can use lower bandwidth(s) in the session, depending on the input signal.
